Traditional Newtonian fluids are characterized by a linear relationship between stress and strain rate, governed by a constant viscosity: $$ oldsymbol{	au} = \mu \dot{ oldsymbol{\gamma}}$$ where $ oldsymbol{	au}$ is the stress tensor, $\mu$ is the viscosity, and $\dot{ oldsymbol{\gamma}}$ is the strain rate tensor. For non-Newtonian fluids, this relationship becomes more complex: 1. **Viscoplastic fluids (e.g., Bingham plastics, Herschel-Bulkley fluids)** exhibit a yield stress $	au_y$ that must be exceeded before flow occurs: $$ oldsymbol{	au} =  egin{cases} 	au_{y} rac{\dot{ oldsymbol{\gamma}}}{|\dot{ oldsymbol{\gamma}}|} + K|\dot{ oldsymbol{\gamma}}|^{n-1}\dot{ oldsymbol{\gamma}}, & 	ext{if } | oldsymbol{	au}| > 	au_y \ \dot{ oldsymbol{\gamma}} = 0, & 	ext{if } | oldsymbol{	au}| \leq 	au_y \end{cases} $$ 2. **Viscoelastic fluids** exhibit memory effects, with stress depending on the deformation history. A common model is the Oldroyd-B model: $$ oldsymbol{	au} + \lambda \overset{
abla}{ oldsymbol{	au}} = \mu \left( \dot{ oldsymbol{\gamma}} + \lambda_r \overset{
abla}{\dot{ oldsymbol{\gamma}}} ight)$$ where $\lambda$ is the relaxation time, $\lambda_r$ is the retardation time, and $\overset{
abla}{ oldsymbol{	au}}$ denotes the upper-convected derivative of the stress tensor.

Key dimensionless parameters include:
> 
> - **Deborah number (De)**: Ratio of relaxation time to flow time scale
> - **Elasto-capillary number (Ec)**: Ratio of elastic forces to surface tension
> - **Ohnesorge number (Oh)**: Ratio of viscous forces to inertial and capillary forces
> - **Bond number (Bond)**: Ratio of gravitational forces to surface tension
